## About this Noiselog

Small technical updates, reviews, and insights into the things we are working
on. Written by Chris.

You can [subscribe to this page via
RSS]($link.page('noiselog').alternative('rss')).

This page lists entries for the year 2025, for past or future entries consult
the [noiselog archive](/noiselog/).

## [Beatboxing mics]($section.id("2025-11-29T16:54:00"))

Before we started our songwriting session today, Mike and I tried out a few
different ways of recording his beatboxing. There are plenty more microphones
I want to test, but in our whole collection it seems the humble SM58 handles it
best — somehow sounding better than the fancier options.

To be clear, it’s not perfect. The low-end isn’t as full as we’d like, and it
doesn’t capture every tiny detail, but it delivers a punch that nothing else
managed. And for beatboxing, those natural percussive transients are the holy
grail. After all, more bass can always be added later with triggered parallel
pitch-shifting or layered synths.

So while we’re writing, Mike is just using the same setup we use for live shows
with the loop-station. I simply track the main outputs and match the tempo in
Reaper.

-- Chris

## [Gotta' get that toan]($section.id("2025-11-28T19:08:00"))

All of this is just for the feel of the instrument. I care little for the
authenticity of a guitar tone, especially as guitarists are usually the only
people who care.

For this songwriting Reaper template, instead of firing up the old Voxes, I’m
using my two favourite amp-sim plugins: IK Multimedia’s [AmpliTube][amplitube]
and Native Instruments’ [Guitar Rig][guitarrig]. AmpliTube offers a downright
delicious recreation of the AC30, and Guitar Rig comes loaded with gloriously
odd presets for ambient, textural, and effect-driven sounds.

There are a couple of little tricks I use to make these digital tools feel more
natural while I’m playing through them. First, I always drop a modelled
compressor between the power amp and the speaker sim. I usually reach for some
flavour of 1176 when I want that funky, snappy bite, and a Vari-Mu (a tube
compressor) when I’m after _“moar toan”_. That’s a huge part of what a valve
power amp does: warmly squeezing the signal into something that breathes.

The other trick — easily my most overused move in my entire plugin toolbelt —
is sticking a good saturation plugin on the guitar bus. Usually FabFilter
[Saturn][saturn], because it just works.

All of this is purely for the feel of the instrument. I care very little about
the supposed “authenticity” of a guitar tone, especially given that guitarists
tend to be the only people who notice.

-- Chris

[amplitube]: https://www.ikmultimedia.com/products/amplitube5/
[guitarrig]: https://www.native-instruments.com/en/products/komplete/guitar/guitar-rig-7-pro/
[saturn]: https://www.fabfilter.com/products/saturn-2-multiband-distortion-saturation-plug-in


## [Write space]($section.id("2025-11-27T21:06:00"))

How can I create the best environment for us to write music?

Recently, the three of us have been on a proper songwriting streak. It’s been
so productive that we’ve shelved all our other plans and thrown ourselves into
making our first EP. Step one is simple: write more songs for it. We already
have a healthy pile of individual ideas and half-finished pieces, but while
we’re in this creative gear, it feels right to carve out time for fresh
material that sounds like _"Polgar."_

I want to catch as much of that new music as possible the moment it sparks.
To help with that, I’ve started building a template in Reaper. Plenty of
producers swear by templates in their DAW (Digital Audio Workstation), but
I’ve never been the biggest fan. There’s something romantic about opening a
blank project with no blueprint and no expectations. Still, once multiple
people are involved and momentum is precious, a bit of structure goes a long
way.

So now I’m retraining my _"blank page"_ instincts. The template isn’t a cage;
it’s more like staff lines to write on, or graph paper that lets you draw
freely without losing the thread.

-- Chris

## [Sitemap]($section.id("2025-11-26T09:17:00"))

Is it necessary to create a `sitemap.xml` file for a static site in 2025?
Probably not, but if we want to be good internet citizens, we should conform
to all the things the little robots crave. This site already has a
`robots.txt`, so that box is ticked.

Creating a sitemap is easy once your site is online. There are websites and
tools that iterate through all your pages — dynamic or static — and forge a
perfectly serviceable file. But it took me far too long to find an offline,
static-site sitemap generator, so I’m building my own.

The goal is that each time I deploy the site, [Zine][zine] will do its thing
and generate the public folder, then my sitemap tool will scan it and create
an up-to-date `sitemap.xml`. Should be fairly simple to implement (famous last
words).

I’m writing it in [Zig][zig], of course. It makes sense to use the same
toolchain as Zine, and I’m rather fond of the language. I’m naming it
[Pathwright][pathwright].


-- Chris

[zine]: /blog/first-post/
[zig]: https://ziglang.org/
[pathwright]: https://github.com/sonro/pathwright

## [Pick a colour]($section.id("2025-11-25T10:09:43"))

Any new artist needs a recognisable art style, and it certainly helps to stay
consistent across photos, logos, videos, fonts -- even the way you write. These
things can evolve, of course. Traditionally (since the 60s), bands have tied
changes in their visual identity to album cycles. I’m not convinced the
_“album”_ should be the milestone musicians organise themselves around
anymore, but that’s a conversation for another day.

Once you’ve settled on a colour you like, building a palette around it has
never been easier. You don’t need a degree in colour theory to open up
[coolors.co][coolors] or [color-hex.com][color-hex] and happily experiment
until something fits your aesthetic.

It didn’t take us long to land on the red we wanted. A mix of French New Wave
posters, Tarantino’s stylised grit, and some striking Queen’s Gambit fan art
nudged us towards the rather seductive
**[#c60420]($text.attrs("polgar-red"))**.

-- Chris

[coolors]: https://coolors.co/
[color-hex]: https://www.color-hex.com/

## [Hello, World!]($section.id("2025-11-24T16:19:00"))

What the hell is a noiselog?

> It's like a devlog. So what's a devlog?  _"A devlog is a blog or diary that
> updates an audience on the development progress of a project, typically a
> video game, website, or app."_ 
> 
> [Wiktionary][devlog]

**Why do this?** I like microblogging, nerding out about music, coding, audio
tech, and how musicians work behind the scenes. The more in-depth stuff will
probably end up in the [blog]($link.page("blog")). Also, with this outlet, I
can avoid nerding out on social media... too much.

-- Chris

[devlog]: https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/devlog
